notesStmt.note: Incipit: Hier begint onser wrouwen ghetide (f. 13r).

Notes in a later hand (to 1684) on final 2 leaves comprise a family history of the Brantzum family of Friesland. A transcription of this chronicle of the Brantzum family and corrections to the description of the ms. by Philip E. Webber have been made by Lydia Wierda and shelved with the manuscript.

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Flemish hours of the Virgin Mary, with calendar of Utrecht, translation of Geert Groote.

supportDesc.extent: 158 leaves : 158 x 107 (95 x 61) mm. bound to 164 x 106 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Parchment, iii (paper) + 158 + i (parchment); [1-159]; modern foliation in pencil, lower right recto.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a Gothic book hand with notes in a later hand on the last folio and the back endleaf.

decoDesc.decoNote: Rubrics in red, alternating red and blue capitals, illuminated historiated initials with illuminated borders of Madonna and Child (f. 13r), Gregorian Man of Sorrows (f. 47r), Christ in the attitude of Benediction (f. 75r), Pentecost (f. 95r), The Last Judgment (f. 111r), and Hell's Mouth (f. 127r); one initial appears to be unfinished (f. 69r). Water damage to a number of illuminations and borders.
Historiated initial, Initial H, Madonna and Child, f. 13r
Historiated initial, Initial H, Gregorian Man of Sorrows, f. 47r
Historiated initial, Christ in the attitude of Benediction, Initial M, f. 75r
Historiated initial, Pentecost, Initial H, f. 95r
Historiated initial, The Last Judgment, Initial H, f. 111r
Inhabited border, Angels and The Dead Rising, f. 111r
Historiated initial, Mouth of Hell, Initial M, f. 127r

binding.p: Contemporary blind stamped goatskin over wooden boards, lower cover detached, upper cover nearly detached.

origin.p: Written in the northeast Netherlands (dialect), 15th century (Webber).

history.provenance: Formerly owned by James Laurie; Paul-Louis Feiss (bookplates, inside upper cover).
Sold at auction at Parke-Bernet Galleries, 15 Dec. 1953 (catalog 1487), lot 390.
